# Positioning

> Your one-line positioning and the language that grounds comments, DMs, and the call invite.
> **Focus areas ≠ content pillars.** The **focus areas** below are your strategic territories (the
> outcomes you sell) — `/post` picks the active one from the "I help" statement you give at post time,
> then writes within that area's shift. Your **content pillars** (the recurring post themes/angles you
> rotate through) are *derived during `/onboard`* and live in the Signature lenses section below.
> One post = one focus area (the outcome) + one content pillar/lens (the angle).

## One-liner (problem → solution → outcome)

Which **focus area(s)** a post belongs to is driven by the input — the "I help …" statement plus the
raw content/context the owner gives. Match that input to one or more of the focus areas below, by
relevance; don't force a fixed count. Each focus area carries its own "I help" line to match against.
Keep the post itself built on a single clear shift so short-form stays punchy, even when it touches
more than one area. (The *angle* — which content pillar/lens to write it through — comes from the
Signature lenses section.)

## Focus areas (strategic territories)

> Five focus areas. Each is a stranger-to-believer argument: name the trap, name the shift. `/post`
> tags a post with the focus area(s) the input is relevant to — one or more, driven by the "I help"
> statement and the content. It writes the opener inside the most relevant shift and keeps a single
> clear reframe ("from X → to Y") as the post's spine. Broad → Niche → Deep: open broad enough that
> most professionals see themselves, then narrow to the focus area's specific audience, then go deep
> on the one shift. (These are *not* your content pillars — pillars are the recurring themes derived
> in `/onboard`, below.)

1. **[ Focus area name ]** *(e.g. Business Transformation)*
   - **I help:** [ who ] [ do / achieve / escape ] [ what ].
   - **Audience:** [ the specific person this speaks to ].
   - **Shift:** from [ the trap they're in ] → to [ the outcome they want ].

2. **[ Focus area name ]** *(e.g. Career Expansion)*
   - **I help:** [ who ] [ do / achieve / escape ] [ what ].
   - **Audience:** [ the specific person this speaks to ].
   - **Shift:** from [ the trap ] → to [ the outcome ].

3. **[ Focus area name ]** *(e.g. Future Readiness)*
   - **I help:** [ who ] [ do / achieve / escape ] [ what ].
   - **Audience:** [ the specific person this speaks to ].
   - **Shift:** from [ the trap ] → to [ the outcome ].

4. **[ Focus area name ]** *(e.g. Execution Design)*
   - **I help:** [ who ] [ do / achieve / escape ] [ what ].
   - **Audience:** [ the specific person this speaks to ].
   - **Shift:** from [ the trap ] → to [ the outcome ].

5. **[ Focus area name ]** *(e.g. Personal Evolution)*
   - **I help:** [ who ] [ do / achieve / escape ] [ what ].
   - **Audience:** [ the specific person this speaks to ].
   - **Shift:** from [ the trap ] → to [ the outcome ].
   - **⚠ Compliance note if applicable:** [ e.g. if this focus area touches regulated territory, note
     which qa-gate mode applies and what to keep out ].

## Weekly content calendar (theme + objective + pillar focus, fixed by weekday)

> Owner data — the single store for **Theme**, **Objective**, and **Pillar focus**, all FIXED by
> weekday (not overridden per post). The **theme** sets a post's intent/posture; the **objective** is
> the standing reason for that theme; the **pillar focus** is the standing talking territory for that
> day; the **focus area(s)** map it to the outcome sold. `/post` and the `linkedin-post-creator` agent
> read Theme + Objective + Pillar focus from here by weekday, and take only the **Topic / Angle** from
> `content-calendar.md` (or the owner) per date. To change any of the three fixed fields, amend this
> section. Edit freely as the strategy evolves.

- **Monday — [ Theme, e.g. Empowering & Affirmation ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ the recurring topics for this day — e.g. mindset · identity shift · the trap
  you help people escape ].
  **Objective:** [ why this theme on this day — e.g. reset the audience's mindset at the start of
  the week; help them see the trap and want out ].
  Maps to focus areas: [ list the focus areas above that this day draws on ].

- **Tuesday — [ Theme, e.g. Personal Story ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ e.g. your origin story · turning points · lived experience of the shift ].
  **Objective:** [ e.g. humanise your authority; build trust through real experience, not claims ].
  Maps to focus area: [ list ].

- **Wednesday — [ Theme, e.g. Expertise ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ e.g. how-to · systems · frameworks · practical tools ].
  **Objective:** [ e.g. teach one concrete, actionable thing; create "I need this" moments ].
  Maps to focus areas: [ list ].
  **⚠ Compliance:** [ note if any pillar territory here touches regulated content — e.g. financial
  concepts require concept-only treatment, no products/returns ].

- **Thursday — [ Theme, e.g. Authority & Thought Leadership ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ e.g. contrarian takes · the bigger picture · what the industry gets wrong ].
  **Objective:** [ e.g. challenge beliefs; position you as someone who thinks differently and is
  worth listening to ].
  Maps to focus areas: [ list ].

- **Friday — [ Theme, e.g. Personal Growth ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ e.g. reflection · internal shifts · what you're still learning ].
  **Objective:** [ e.g. end the week with an emotional note; show growth in progress, not just
  results ].
  Maps to focus areas: [ list ].

- **Sunday — [ Theme, e.g. Practical Clarity & Life Decisions ].**
  **Pillar focus:** [ e.g. real decisions · life design · the things people avoid thinking about ].
  **Objective:** [ e.g. use real situations to show how decisions compound; make the abstract
  concrete and personal ].
  Maps to focus areas: [ list ].
  **⚠ Compliance:** [ note any regulated territory for Sunday's pillars ].

## Words you use / avoid
- Use: [ concrete nouns and verbs that match your world — e.g. "land the client," "the business
  stops when you stop," "one employer, one decision and it's gone" ].
- Avoid: the `anti-ai.md` banned list. No em dashes inside sentences. No motivational-poster
  endings. Close on a specific insight or one clear action.

## Content pillars / Signature lenses (the value-generation angles)

> **These are your content pillars** — the recurring themes/angles you post through, *derived during
> `/onboard`* (Step 2c). 4-6 repeatable angles you see the world through; the writing skills rotate a
> different lens per variation to satisfy the "lived experience OR signature lens" rule. The focus area
> (above) sets the *outcome* a post sells; the content pillar/lens sets the *angle* it's told from.

1. **[ Lens name — e.g. "The Design Problem" ]**
   [ 1-2 sentences: what this lens sees that others miss. e.g. "Most people treat the bottleneck
   as a people problem. This lens reframes it as a systems problem — the operations were never
   designed to run without the founder." ]
   **Use as a lens:** [ The question to run a draft through — e.g. "Where is the design missing?
   What would need to be true for this to run without them?" ]

2. **[ Lens name ]**
   [ description ]
   **Use as a lens:** [ question ]

